    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-01-23T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-01-23T04:00:00-05:00" n="858"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d858">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">894.00/678: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-01-23T18:00:00+09:00"
                            >January 23, 1937—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 23—7:09 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>21. Embassy’s 16, January 23, 1 a.m.<note n="5" xml:id="d858fn5">Not
                        printed.</note> Hirota presented collective resignation of the Cabinet to
                    the Emperor this afternoon but not yet accepted. Resignation was due to the War
                    Minister’s refusal to accept any form of compromise with the political parties.
                    Successor to Hirota uncertain but Ugaki<note n="6" xml:id="d858fn6">Gen.
                        Kazushige Ugaki, formerly Japanese Governor General of Korea.</note>
                    prominently mentioned. Comments later.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Nanking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
